    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "All that would change is that usage could look something like this:\r\n```lua\r\nvim.notify({\r\n    { \"some message\", log_level, opts }\r\n    { \"another message\", a_different_log_level, other_opts }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis stems from a discussion we are having here: https://github.com/nvim-lua/plenary.nvim/pull/188. The general idea is that we split notifications into two components. For lack of a better term call them a \"provider\" and a \"consumer.\" What would happen is that notifications are sent through `vim.notify`, the same way it is used right now, but then users could override that with a consumer to render notifications as they'd like. For more details see the discussion linked above.\r\n\r\n@clason correct me if I've described anything inaccurately :)\r\nCC @teto ",
